 to compensate for the one that’s missing in her memory. She travels to San Diego, where her family vacationed with her father right before he died. She researches, interviews, and meditates, all while facing down the two traumatic memories that defined her early life. The result is an experimental memoir that upends our understanding of the genre. Rather than recount a childhood, The Memory Sessions attempts to create one from research, archives, imagination, and the memories of others. Published by Bucknell University Press. Distributed worldwide by Rutgers University Press.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aAutobiographyxAuthorshipxPsychological aspectsvCase studies. 0aFathersxDeathxPsychological aspectsvCase studies. 0aFiresxPsychological aspectsvCase studies. 0aMemory disordersxPatientszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aPsychic trauma in childrenvCase studies. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / General.2bisacsh  amemoir, memory loss, amnesia, traumatic memory, childhood memory, parental loss, childhood trauma, loss of father, memory recovery, writers' memoir, transformative memoir, immersion writing, cognition, memory, cognitive psychology, neuropsychology, autobiography, mind, brain, experimental autobiography.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065352640uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978168448151440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781684481514423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781684481514/original  a978-3-11-065352-6  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK